  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="faq-container">
        <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <p class="section-subtitle">
          Common questions about our custom software development process in the
          UAE.
        </p>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <details>
            <summary
              >What is the difference between IoT and embedded systems?</summary
            >
            An embedded system is a dedicated computing system built into a physical
            device to perform a specific function — such as the controller in an industrial
            machine, a medical device, or a smart appliance. IoT (Internet of Things)
            extends this concept by connecting those devices to a network — typically
            the internet — enabling remote monitoring, control, and data collection.
            Many IoT deployments involve embedded systems at the device level combined
            with cloud platforms for data aggregation and analytics.
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary
              >What industries do you serve with IoT solutions in the UAE?</summary
            >
            Common sectors include industrial manufacturing and production (predictive
            maintenance, process monitoring), commercial real estate (building management
            systems, energy monitoring, access control), logistics and fleet management
            (asset tracking, cold chain monitoring), smart agriculture (irrigation
            control, environmental sensing), and utilities and infrastructure (smart
            metering, pipeline monitoring). We also work with developers on smart
            home and smart building integrations for residential and hospitality projects.
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>How do you ensure IoT devices are secure?</summary>
            Security for IoT systems includes several layers: device-level security
            (hardware attestation, secure boot, encrypted storage), communication
            security (TLS encryption, certificate-based device authentication), cloud-side
            security (API authentication, network segmentation, anomaly detection),
            and operational security (secure OTA updates with rollback capability,
            audit logging). We design all of these into the system from the start
            rather than attempting to add them after deployment.
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary
              >Can IoT systems operate in UAE outdoor and industrial
              environments?</summary
            >
            Yes. We select hardware and specify enclosures rated for the temperature,
            humidity, and ingress protection requirements of each deployment environment.
            For UAE outdoor installations, this typically means specifying components
            rated to operate at temperatures above 60°C, IP65 or higher enclosure
            ratings for dust and moisture protection, and UV-resistant materials for
            exposed installations.
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary
              >How do you connect IoT devices that are in remote locations
              without reliable internet?</summary
            >
            We have experience with a range of connectivity options suited to different
            range, bandwidth, and power requirements. For wide-area deployments in
            remote locations, we work with cellular IoT (4G/LTE-M/NB-IoT), LoRaWAN,
            and satellite connectivity options. For local-area deployments, WiFi,
            Zigbee, and wired Ethernet are common choices. In many cases, we design
            hybrid architectures where devices store data locally and sync when connectivity
            is available.
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary
              >What does a typical IoT project engagement look like?</summary
            >
            It typically starts with a requirements and site assessment — understanding
            the physical environment, connectivity landscape, data requirements, and
            integration points with existing systems. We then produce a system architecture
            document and hardware specification, followed by a prototype phase to
            validate the core functionality before full deployment. After prototype
            validation, we move to production build and deployment, followed by commissioning,
            testing, and handover with documentation and training.
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
